snippet.title: Mitsubishi driver decides he wants to dance with Arkansas State Police
snippet.description:
Trooper's Narrative:

I WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON U.S. HIGHWAY 65 NEAR THE CITY LIMITS OF HARRISON WHEN I OBSERVED
V1 TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND AT 80 MPH IN A 45 MPH ZONE. I ACTIVATED MY EMERGENCY LIGHTS AND SIREN
AND TURNED MY UNIT AROUND TO STOP V1. AFTER CATCHING UP TO V1 I OBSERVED BRAKES LIGHTS AND A
RIGHT TURN SIGNAL COMING FROM V1. I TURNED MY SIREN OFF BELIEVING V1 WAS GOING TO STOP. V1
CONTINUED SOUTHBOUND, I ACTIVATED MY SIREN AGAIN. V1 SIGNALED AS IF HE WAS GOING TO STOP, AND
ONCE AGAIN I TURNED MY SIREN OFF. V1 THEN USED THE TURN LANE TO NAVIGATE AROUND VEHICLES AT A
STOP LIGHT. I ACTIVATED MY SIREN AND NOTIFIED DISPATCH THAT I WAS IN PURSUIT OF V1. V1 CONTINUED
SOUTH THROUGH HARRISON ON MAIN STREET. V1 WAS SPEEDING APPROXIMATELY 10 MPH ABOVE POSTED
SPEED ZONES WHILE IN THE CITY LIMITS. I CHASED V1 THROUGH NON-POPULATED RESIDENTIAL
NEIGHBORHOODS FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 MINUTES. AFTER CLEARING THE NEIGHBORHOOD WE ENTERED
CAPPS RD AND TRAVELED TOWARD STATE HIGHWAY 397. V1 MADE A RIGHT TURN ONTO S.H. 397 AND BEGAN
PASSING CARS. I WAITED FOR VEHICLES TO BE CLEAR OF THE ROADWAY AND PERFORMED A PIT ON V1 BY
MOVING TO THE RIGHT REAR SIDE OF HIS VEHICLE AND USING MY DRIVER-SIDE PIT BUMPER TO MOVE V1 OFF
HIS COURSE. V1 ROTATED A HALF TURN CLOCKWISE HITTING MY PASSENGER SIDE. V1 THEN ROLLED
BACKWARDS AND BECAME PERPENDICULAR IN THE ROADWAY. I USED THE FRONT OF MY PUSH BAR TO "PIN" V1s
PASSENGER SIDE AND KEEP HIM FROM MOVING. HARRISON PD UNITS HELPED BOX HIM IN. S1 WAS REMOVED
FROM V1 AND PLACED UNDER ARREST WITHOUT INCIDENT.

snippet.title: FLEEING with Felony Warrant:  PIT Maneuver into Church sign and telephone pole #pit #chase #police
snippet.description:
Trooper's Report:

I WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON CENTRAL AVE. WHEN I OBSERVED V1 HAD A CRACKED WINDSHIELD AND
 EXPIRED TAGS. I POSITIONED MYSELF BEHIND V1 AND ACTIVATED MY EMERGENCY LIGHTS. V1 THEN TURNED
 ONTO S. MAIN STREET. I FOLLOWED V1 TO SOUTH WALNUT AND HIT MY SIREN TO GET HIS ATTENTION. AFTER
 ALERTING V1 OF MY PRESENCE HE RAPIDLY ACCELERATED IN AN ATTEMPT TO FLEE. V1 THEN TRAVELED ONTO
 E. SOUTH AVE. 

BEING FAMILIAR WITH THE AREA AND KNOWING WE WERE RAPIDLY APPROACHING A
 NEIGHBORHOOD I QUICKLY MADE THE DECISION TO PERFORM A TVI ON V1. I USED MY PUSH BAR TO MAKE
 CONTACT WITH V1S REAR. AFTER CONTACT, V1 BEGAN TO ROTATE COUNTERCLOCKWISE HITTING A TELEPHONE
 POLE, AND OVERTURNED ONE TIME LANDING UPRIGHT FACING THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION IN A CHURCH PARKING
 LOT. S1 THEN EXITED THE VEHICLE FROM THE REAR DRIVER-SIDE DOOR AND LAID FACE DOWN ON THE PARKING
 LOT. 

AFTER S1 EXITED, V1 BEGAN TO ROLL WESTBOUND HITTING A SIGN BELONGING TO THE CHURCH OF THE
 NAZARENE, CONTINUED ACROSS A RESIDENTIAL LAWN AND COLLIDED WITH A TREE. S1 CONTINUED LYING ON
 THE GROUND FACE DOWN MOANING AND UNABLE TO CLEARLY COMMUNICATE WITH ME.

 S1 WAS TAKEN TO THE NORTH ARKANSAS REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER AND CHARGED WITH: 

FLEEING IN VEHICLE,
 NO INSURANCE, RECKLESS DRIVING, NO SEATBELT, THEFT OF PROPERTY $1000, OWNER FAIL TO REGISTER,
 DEFECTIVE TAIL LAMPS. S1 ALSO HAD A FELONY WARRANT OUT OF THE NEWTON COUNTY SHERIFFS OFFICE.

 FELONY WARRANT SERVED

 THE CHURCH OF THE NAZARENE SIGN HAS AN ESTIMATED REPLACEMENT COST OF $1000 AND THE TELEPHONE
 POLE FROM WINDSTREAM HAS AN ESTIMATED REPLACEMENT COST OF $1500.

snippet.title: Harrison, AR: A Walking Tour of History
snippet.description:
Harrison, Arkansas was founded in 1869 by Marcus LaRue Harrison, a Union officer during the Civil War. The town was originally named Stifler Springs, but it was renamed Harrison in 1870 after Harrison, who had surveyed the area for the railroad. Harrison grew rapidly in the late 19th century, and it became the county seat of Boone County in 1876. The city was a major center for the lumber industry, and it also had a number of other industries, including railroads, coal mining, and manufacturing.

Jak się okazuje, prawda jak zwykle leży gdzieś po środku i mimo, że w Harrison, faktycznie można spotkać się z przejawami skrajnych poglądów, mimo że część jego mieszkańców należy do różnych ekstremalnie prawicowych grup, to jednak są oni w mniejszości.

Niestety wizerunkowa siła ich oddziaływania, a szczególnie siła i pozycja pastora Thomasa Robba, mieszkającego w oddalonym o 15 mil Zinc wielkiego mistrza KKK, sprawiają, że Harrison jeszcze długo będzie borykało się z problemami o podłożu rasistowskim.

W tym materiale zabieramy Was na wycieczkę do Harrison oraz do Zinc, podczas której omawiamy całe tło problemów tych dwóch miejscowości znajdujących się w północno-zachodniej części stanu Arkansas.

Opowiemy Ci o tej części USA, która skutecznie opiera się nowoczesności, jest dzika i autentyczna. Jadąc od Tennessee do Mississippi odwiedzimy klasyczne dinery, porozmawiamy z typowymi redneckami i zwiedzimy miejsca, w których grały legendy bluesa i country. snippet.title: Inside the Forgotten Dogpatch USA Theme Park
snippet.description:
Join us as we visit the Boone County Heritage Museum in Harrison, Arkansas to check out the Dogpatch USA Theme Park exhibit.  Dogpatch USA was a theme park located in northwest Arkansas along State Highway 7 between the cities of Harrison and Jasper, an area known today as Marble Falls. It was based on the comic strip Li'l Abner, created by cartoonist Al Capp and set in a fictional village called Dogpatch. The park opened in 1968, and closed in 1993.  During the 25 years of business, the park brought in tourists from all parts of North America.  Characters like Li'l Abner, Daisy Mae, Mammy & Pappy Yokum and lots of other hillbilly named characters roamed the park picking fun with visitors.  There were unusual rides around the property as well as several shows to entertain everyone.  Even though it has been nearly 30 years since the park closed in 1993, people still talk about the park and the memories their family made there.  Once in a while, I run across someone who saw me play drums on the Riverbend Music Show there.  Our show cast members for the Riverbend Music Show were Gary Van Meter on the Steel Guitar, John Payne on Piano, Randy Hall on Lead Guitar, Mel Bartlow on Bass Guitar, Jereme Dison on drums, and vocals by Bryce Gage, Brenda Maynard, James Walls, Jackson Nightingale and Ken Bevins.  My time working with the show at Dogpatch USA will be days that I will cherish for the rest of my life.  I hope you enjoy this video.  I would love to hear your comments about your memories of the park in the comments.
